    <abstract>
      <!-- can be changed via merge in the assembly -->
      <para>
        This topic guides you through starting an automated installation using &agama;. You can
        initiate the process either by specifying boot parameters or by using the &agama;
        command-line interface.
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>
  <section xml:id="initiating-agama-unattended-installation">
    <title>Initiating the unattended installation</title>
    <procedure xml:id="proc-initiating-agama-unattended-installation">
      <title>Initiating the unattended installation</title>
      <step>
        <para>
          Start the installation using kernel boot parameters.
        </para>
        <para>
          Add the <literal>inst.auto</literal> parameter to the kernel command line to specify the
          location of the &agama; profile:
        </para>
<screen>&prompt.sudo;<command>linux inst.auto=<replaceable>http://example.net/profile.json</replaceable></command></screen>
        <para>
          This method is suitable for PXE boot setups, custom ISO builds, or cloud-init workflows.
        </para>
        <para>
          For more information on boot options, refer to
          <link xlink:href="https://agama-project.github.io/docs/user/boot_options"></link>.
        </para>
      </step>
      <step>
        <para>
          Start the installation using the &agama; CLI.
        </para>
        <substeps>
          <step>
            <para>
              Validate the profile:
            </para>
<screen>&prompt.sudo;<command>agama profile validate <replaceable>profile.json</replaceable></command></screen>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              Import the profile with the following command:
            </para>
<screen>&prompt.sudo;<command>agama profile import
<replaceable>profile.json</replaceable></command></screen>
            <para>
              If importing a dynamic profile using a Jsonnet file, &agama; handles dynamic
              features such as rules, classes, and embedded Ruby (ERB) templates.
            </para>
            <para>
              For information on the supported URL types for validation and import, refer to
              <link xlink:href="https://agama-project.github.io/docs/user/urls"></link>.
            </para>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              Initiate the installation with the following command:
            </para>
<screen>&prompt.sudo;<command>agama install</command></screen>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              Monitor the installation with the following command:
            </para>
<screen>&prompt.sudo;<command>agama monitor</command></screen>
          </step>
        </substeps>
      </step>
    </procedure>
  </section>
